column168: Description Of Events

XPO Logistics terminal XSA experienced a UN1760 Clothesline Fresh BLD 2 release from a 5-gallon poly pail and a Non-Regulated Xcelente release from a 2-liter poly jug. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed all 5-gallons of the UN1760 Clothesline Fresh BLD 2 released as all as all 2-liters of the Xcelente released together. The products impacted a 12’ x 4’ area of the trailer floor and a 12’ x 4’ area of the concrete lot below due to forklift punctures. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged empty jugs and spend absorbents were then collected into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: TILX 160815 was reported to be leaking from the Bottom Outlet Valve (BOV). An estimated 2 ounces of product leaked from the BOV nozzle threads and cap. The cap was less then tool tight, adding Teflon tape to the threads and tightening the cap stopped the release. The BOV was in the closed position. Product in the nozzle was residue from off-loading operations. The shipper's facility is next the location of release. The shipper will route the car back to their facility and preform an additional inspection.

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED STAINED IN APPEARANCE BY THE PKG DIV SUPERVISOR AT THE BOXLINE-3 CLERK STATION. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND CONTACTED THE DMP. A RESPONDER ARRIVED WITHIN 2 MINUTES, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 POLY 1-GAL JUGS WAS LOOSE BY A FULL ROTATION, CAUSING APPROX. 12 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO SPILL THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 44LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

On September 1, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1789 was crushed during transit and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Works, Inc. (EWI) to remediate the impacted site. EWI personnel deployed neutralizing, granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor and swept them in with hand tools. All freight was wiped down and repalletized for further handling by R+L terminal personnel. All spent absorbents, cleanup debris, and the empty, damaged 5-gallon pail were collected and containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drum that was labeled and staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

column168: On September 6, 2023, one (1) 330-gallon tote containing UN1805 was damaged due to falling off the lift gate and released approximately eighty (80) gallons of product to the soil. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from SET Environmental (SET) to remediate the impacted site. SET personnel deployed poly sheeting around the impacted areas and patched the one (1) damaged tote. The crew returned the next day to perform a tote transfer. SET personnel conducted a gravity transfer of the remaining material from the damaged tote into one (1) new 330-gallon tote provided by on-site management. Crews deployed a neutralizing agent to the impacted area. Once neutralized, SET personnel utilized a back hoe to remove the impacted soil. The excavated area was backfilled with clean soil, graded to match pre-existing topography, and covered with erosion matting to promote vegetative growth. All impacted soil was collected and containerized into one (1) roll off and staged on-site pending waste profiling for disposal purposes. One (1) background and one (1) confirmation sample were obtained from the site, placed into laboratory approved containers, and transported under chain of custody protocol to the laboratory.

XPO Logistics terminal XCN experienced a UN3272 Disperbyk-161 release from a 55-gallon steel drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 53-gallons of material released to a 58’ x 10’ area of the concrete lot below the dock and a 15’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas and then collected into (3) 55-gallon metal drums. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon poly overpack. The impacted trailer, concrete lot, and trench drain that flows to the onsite OWS were all pressure washed. All impacted water and skimmed material from the trench drain were collected and containerized into an additional 55-gallon metal drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: When picking up freight to load into trailer, forklift operator placed the forkblades of his forklift into the pallet of freight and when doing so the forkblades struck the bottom of a drum that was staged on the pallet that had fallen in between a broken board on the pallet. When the drum was struck by the forkblade it punctured the drum which in turn contributed to the unintentional release. Spilled material was neutralized and cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container as was the punctured drum.
column169: If a piece of dunnage like a sheet of cardboard was placed on the pallet before the freight was staged on it or better quality pallets were used maybe this unintentional release could have been prevented.

column168: While loading freight into a trailer, forklift operator drove the forkblades of his forklift into the bottom of two drums that were already staged in the trailer consequently puncturing them and contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into recovery containers as were the two punctured drums.
column169: Forklift operators need to pay attention to the clearances of their forklifts including the forkblades to help these types of unintentional releases from occurring. A meeting was held with the dockworkers about this event and what they can do to help prevent these types of unintentional releases going forward.

column168: It appears that the shipment was punctured by a forklift upon moving into the truck for transport  (after being flown). It was not noticed until the next day when it was to be picked up. Shipment was cleaned up by a HAZMAT team        •     AWB#75875343- 28-piece shipment- split between two flights 928/959 on 8/31/23.•  4 pieces on  928, 24 pieces on 959•  Shipment was placed on reefer truck on 8/31•   Driver came to pick up  shipment on 9/2 around 1300, noticed the powder, and immediately refused to pick up shipment.• Faro  Employee Leticia Alvarez went to investigate and began to try to clean up the area. UA management  advised at the time•   Hazchem on site at 6pm for cleanup, 3 damaged boxes removed after clean up  due to punctures in the boxes and leaking.  Hazchem contact: Allan Mandell 330 S.Fairbank Street        Addison IL (630} • Attempted to contact local environmental coordinator at 2:20pm

column168: On September 12, 2023, at 1550 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Dickson, Tennessee regarding the release of approximately (40) gallons of Isopropyl Alcohol 70% (UN1219, 3, II). The shipment had 26 pallets of an unknown amount of boxes. Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed that the release was from 26 crushed cardboard boxes all together containing (312) 16-ounce bottles. The release was due to too much weight on top of the boxes, crushing the boxes and bottles inside, and contained to a 5’x 4’ area of the trailer floor. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (4) 55-gallon DF which was then taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal LSH experienced a customer location release of UN1791 Sodium Hypochlorite 12.5% from a 55-gallon poly drum. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-teaspoon of material released the drum lid only. The vented bung on the drum released due to the drum being tipped over off of the pallet. The drum was re-secured to the pallet for shipment on and wiped down. All impacted absorbent pads were collected and containerized into a 5-gallon poly pail. The waste was transported to the XPO terminal located in Sherman, TX and staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

During the QC process in the warehouse at Veolia's 10 day intransit facility, the drum was removed from the pallet to be weighed. The drum was weighed and set aside for approximately 30 minutes. When the employee returned back to the drum, he noticed a very small pinhole leak coming from the side, rib area of the drum. The leak was minor and the drum was promptly overpacked and the spill was cleaned up.
column169: Veolia will contact the shipper to recommend the use of a packaging type that is better suited to handle the material such as poly drums. It appears that the material currently being stored in the drums at the shipper's location is corroding through the metal containers over time.

column168: SequenceEvent: unload manager called Qa for a Hazmat spill. He said the pallet had tipped over in transit and when the package handler was unloading it the one on the bottom started leaking.  Qa came with spill pads and a tote.  The leaker was put in a tote.  When QA came to clean up spill, we realized that the Hazmat was leaking all the way down the trailer and outside. We immediately called ERTS. Hazmat cleaning company came and cleaned up the spill. They immediately put the leaker in a salvage drum. No pictures were taken and not exactly sure how many leaked out. This leaker also damaged 4 other Hazmat's. DescribePack: The pallet had tipped over during transit causing the Hazmat on the bottom to leak out. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The hazmat was put in a tote and spill pads were put down in the trailer.

On September 1, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3287 was crushed during transit and released approximately less-than one (<1) gallon of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site.  HCE personnel utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the site. All spent absorbents and debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. The damaged 55-gallon drum of product was placed into one (1) 95-gallon drum.

On September 11, 2023, one (!) one-gallon jug of UN2924 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately 3/4-gallon of product to the box, pallet, and floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. The undamaged cargo was staged in a new area for continued processing and shipping. Granular absorbents were deployed to the impacted area and worked in with hand tools. All UN2924-impacted material was collected and containerized into the one (1) 55-gallon drum. The drum was properly labeled and possession of the material was taken by RLC for disposal through their bulk waste stream.

On 09/19/2023, at 1042 hrs. Personnel in the CSXT Ottawa Yard discovered MTZX330221, a residue tank car of Propane, leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated and NGL Supply Wholesale LLC, NRC, Illinois EMA, Ottawa Fire Department were notified.  CHEMTREC Report #2023091900178. (RMS), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the secondary closure not applied and laying on the pressure plate and the A-end liquid line valve open 1/8th of a turn). The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Jamee Spears 501-680-2267). Contractor personnel closed the valve, cleaned the threads of the secondary plug, applied new thread tape and tool tightened it in place. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident (did not) require a special switching move.  No 7.1 is required.  Cause Code: 312 NARRI: 5

column168: AT THE UPS WORLDPORT FACILITY IN LOUISVILLE, KY, A PACKAGE WITH A UN3481 LITHIUM BATTERY MARK WAS BEING SCANNED INTO A FEEDER TRUCK WHEN A HOLE WAS NOTICED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX. UPON REMOVING THE PACKAGE SMOKE WAS THEN OBSERVED COMING FROM THE PACKAGE. OUTER BOX INSPECTION REVEALED NO SIGNS OF A THERMAL EVENT. A TEAR/HOLE IS OBSERVED ON THE BOTTOM OF THE OUTER BOX. INNER BOX INSPECTION REVEALED ONE MACBOOK PRO WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF A THERMAL EVENT. THE MACBOOK SHOWED SIGNS OF MELTING, CHARRING, AND BURN MARKS. THE PADDING SURROUNDING THE MACBOOK WAS PARTIALLY MELTED. THE INSIDE OF THE BOX ALSO SHOWED SOME SIGNS OF CHARRING. DOCUMENTATION WITH THE PACKAGE SHOWS THE MACBOOK HAD UNDERGONE DISPLAY AND LID ANGLE SENSOR REPLACEMENT UNDER WARRANTY BY APPLECARE SERVICE. THE PACKAGE WAS BEING SHIPPED TO THE ORIGINAL OWNER IN INDIANA. THE PACKAGE HAD PREVIOUSLY FLOWN FROM IAH TO SDF. AN NRC REPORT WAS MADE ON 9/19/2023 UNDER NRC 1379487.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal NRG experienced a UN3266 AFCO 8714 Rave Hydroxy 50% release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 4-gallons of material released to an 8’ x 5’ area of the trailer floor, and a 6' x 4' area of the concrete yard below due to a damaged seal around the port. Citric acid and water solution were utilized to neutralize the impacted areas and then cleaned with absorbents. The product was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all cleanup debris into (2) 30-gallon metal drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On September 12, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon container of UN2922 was crushed during transit and released its full contents to the trailer interior and dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to remediate the impacted site. Crews utilized absorbent pads, a sprayer, and a neutralizing solution to wipe down all freight and the impacted floor of the trailer and dock until the surfaces tested neutral and were sufficiently remediated.  All spent absorbents and cleanup debris were collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums. The one (1) damaged 5-gallon pail of product was placed into one (1) 55-gallon drum. All three (3) containers of waste were labeled appropriately and staged on-site.

column168: On September 19, 2023, at 0420 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by MC Tank Transport Inc personnel in Mobile, Alabama regarding the release of approximately (30) gallon of Farmin DM2470 (Amines, liquid, corrosive, n.o.s. (Alkyl (C12-C14 Dimethylamine) UN2735 8, II) from a tanker.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release.  Upon arrival, contractors confirmed that the release was caused by loose flange bolts on the tanker and was contained to a 50' x 2' area of asphalt, and a 1' x 1' area of nearby soil. Contractors were able to clean up the release with absorbents, pad, and the proper PPE. They used hand tools to scrap the affected soil, and tightened the flange bolts, so the cargo could be forwarded on to the original consignee.  All waste generated was containerized in (2) 55-gallon poly drums which was then taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal. No further remediation of this site is warranted.

column168: When driver went to go hook to trailer in drop lot he noticed liquid coming from trailer on the gravel lot. Driver then notified facility manager and a team was dispatcher out to facilitate the clean up. The trailer was moved to the dock to pull the container off and put on a containment pallet and absorbent was put down to prevent any spread of the material until the team could start the clean up. The response team arrived and had to remove the material from the container and put into a new one. Gravel from the lot had to be removed creating three 55 gallon drums of material. The inner liner of the bag was determined to be damaged from when it was filled causing the release. From the time it was identified to when clean up was complete was approximately 4 hours.
column169: Training was redon on how the material is to be put into the container paying special attention to maintaining the integrity of the liner.

On September 21, 2023, at 0840 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Chattanooga, Tennessee regarding the release of approximately (2) gallons of ORGANIC PEROXIDE TYPE F, LIQUID (UN3109, 5.2) from (1) 55-gallon plastic drum. Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. The release was caused by a missing lid and contained to a 3’ x 53’ area on the trailer floor. Contractors were able to neutralize and clean the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (1) 55-gallon DF, which was then taken offsite by the contractor for proper disposal.

column168: Enviroserve was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 1ft-by-1ft area of the trailer floor and terminal floor and estimated that one (1) gallon of material was released due to damaged valve assembly causing the release of material. Enviroserve personnel transferred the remaining material in the damaged 330-gallon metal tote to eight 55-gallon metal drums. Enviroserve personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted areas and collected the spent material and placed into one of the 55-gallon metal drums. The generated waste was staged onsite in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

On September 19, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1161 was crushed during transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site.  HCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the UN1161-impacted trailer and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents and the damaged pail were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum to be staged onsite disposal by R+L.

On September 19, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1993 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately fifty (50) gallons of product to the trailer floor and parking lot. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Alpha-Omega Training and Compliance (AOTC) to remediate the impacted site. AOTC transferred the damaged drum from the trailer to an 85-gallon overpack for transport and disposal. The crew deployed granular absorbents to the impacted trailer and concrete pavement. AOTC utilized hand tools to collect the spent absorbents into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. AOTC staged the drums onsite to be processed via R+Ls normal waste stream.

On September 20, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1760 was crushed in transit and released approximately 5-gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. TLE personnel deployed granular absorbent to the trailer floor and worked them in with hand tools, utilizing a degreasing agent with absorbent wipes to collect any residual product.  All UN1760 impacted material was collected and containerized in three (3) 35-gallon drums and RLC personnel took possession of the waste to be added to the facility waste stream.

column168: On September 20, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1210 was crushed during transit and released approximately three (3) gallons of product to the trailer interior and adjacent freight. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) to remediate the impacted site. R+L terminal personnel deployed granular absorbents prior to HES' arrival. HES personnel swept in the previously deployed granular absorbents with hand tools. Crews wiped down the impacted trailer interior, pallet, and nearby freight with absorbent pads and a degreaser. All spent absorbents, the pail of solidified product, and any cleanup debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum that was staged in the terminal's waste holding room.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal LHO experienced a UN1866 L010-PPA-33 release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup and containment. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-ounces of material released to the tote body only due to a puncture on the top corner of the tote caused by an unknown source. The product was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one for shipment on. The damaged empty tote was then patched and poly sheeting was placed over the tote for disposal. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The two adhesive pails were placed into a 55-gallon salvage drum. The impacted stretch wrap was also placed into the salvage drum. The remaining pails were undamaged and were restacked and stretch wrapped.

column168: SKIDS STACKED ON TOP OF CARTON CAUSING SPILL

Driver got lost, drove onto a narrow rural road and could not negotiate a sharp tum causing left rear of trailer to leave road and rolled down an embankment. When the trailer overturned, it hit a small tree which had branches that entered the spill dam/ rollover protection area and hit the 3/4 inch air inlet line at the base of the Fort Valve PRD and broke the 3/4 inch stainless steel nipple for the air inlet line. There were no other package failures. At this point the cargo tank lost approximately 300 gallons, ER personnel would not allow us to stop the leak until there the tank was anchored by a recovery unit. We requested a tow truck to anchor it around 5:30 on Wed 9-13-2023, but one was never called. At approximately 7:00 PM, the incident commander decided to put off all efforts on hold until 7:30/8:00 AM the following morning due to location and darkness setting in. Due to no cell phone coverage in the area, we had requested ER personnel made all required ^ notifications to EPA, CaIOES, NRC, etc. California Highway Patrol was IC, Alameda Fire was on site, Ambulance, Fish and Wildlife, local environmental agency, the Sf Water district, etc were all onsite. At 07:30 on 9-14-23, a recovery 65 ton rotator arrived on site to secure the trailer. At approximately 8:30 we were allowed to do damage assessment on the trailer and found the source of the leak, drove a redwood plug onto it and stopped the leak. We then hooked up a 2 inch hose between the discharge line and a 70 barrel vacuum tank. By this time, since plugging was delayed, the cargo tank lost approximately 2,000 gallons of product. Tank was emptied, recovered and uprighted.
column169: Better delivery instructions for these rural deliveries. Better signage for the delivery point and mandate that if the driver gets lost to stop and call dispatch for directions. He was also misdirected by both fire personnel and Pacific Gas and Electric utilies crews when he initially got lost.

column168: During receiving/off-loading at Veolia's facility in Phoenix, AZ Veolia employees observed liquid coming from the bottom a 30 gallon fiber drum that was stacked on top of 55 gallon poly drums. Vials containing liquid COD reagent were packed into a fiber drum with no added absorbent or cushioning material. A 6 mil poly bag containing the vials was used as a liner/inner packaging, but apparently it was not sufficient to stop a release of liquid. The containers were removed from the receiving area and placed into the processing area within facility on a spill containment pallet. Notifications were made to the shipping location with instructions to ship this type of material in poly drums in the future to avoid spillage.
column169: Changes or improved operating procedures include: 1) Review proper shipping techniques frequently with all locations and customers shipping to Veolia and 2) Retrain employees as necessary on proper packaging of vials containing liquids.

On September 22, 2023, two (2) 50-pound bags of UN3262 were damaged in a load shift and released approximately one (1) cup of product to the loading dock. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. HCE personnel utilized hand tools to sweep up the spilled product and debris. The two (2) 50-pound bags and all waste was containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum for disposal.

On September 22, 2023, two (2) 5-gallon pails of UN3265 were crushed in transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from SET Environmental (SET) to remediate the impacted site.  The damaged jugs were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal. Crews deployed a neutralizing agent to the impacted area and utilized absorbent wipes to remove residual product from the remaining two (2) undamaged jugs. All UN3265-impacted materials were collected and containerized into one (1) additional 55-gallon drum for disposal.

On September 26, 2023, three (3) 5-gallon pails of UN1993 were damaged during transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Response Management Services (RMS) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the impacted are and worked them in using hand tools. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum and one (1) 95-gallon overpack for disposal purposes.

column168: On September 26, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN2735 was punctured and released approximately fifty (50) gallons of product to the trailer floor and concrete parking lot. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to remediate the impacted site.  ES placed the damaged drum into one (1) 85-gallon overpack for transport and disposal. ES deployed a neutralizing agent and absorbents to the trailer floor and concrete parking lot. The crew utilized absorbent pads to wipe underneath the trailer. ES collected the spent absorbents into five (5) drums for transport and disposal. On September 28, 2023, ES returned to the site. ES utilized a combination of a neutralizer, absorbent wipes, and hand tools to remove the residue buildup generated from the original cleanup. The crew placed the spent neutralizer and absorbents into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. ES staged the drum onsite to be processed via R+L's normal waste stream.

column168: A Veolia driver initially picked up the drum in question on 9/5/2023 from the offeror and the trailer was used to pick up other materials on 9/12/23. The driver noticed that there was some liquid on the front of the trailer along with oily stains on the back of the trailer. Veolia personnel started to remove the drums from the trailer and identified the leaking drum which was located at the nose of the trailer. The leaking drum was a 55 gal metal drum with a pin hole leak that appeared to occur from potentially rubbing/impact against another drum during transportation which was a weak spot due to corrosion. The driver made multiple stops that day and he has stated that he did not notice any staining on the back-end of the trailer when he loaded addition drums at each stop. Also he did not notice any oily material near or around the front of the trailer during those stops. We are unsure of the duration of the spill but based on the quantity still left in the drum, roughly 5 gallons had leaked out. The drum was placed into a salvage drum and the spill clean up was completed by the Veolia in-house crew.  Most of the material was contained inside the trailer with minimal amounts outside of the trailer.  There was no evidence of a any spill on the ground itself.
column169: Based on the investigation, the drums are stored outdoors at the customer site which contributed to some corrosion and likely caused some weak spots on the drum. The driver stated that there was some surface rust on the drum but nothing that may have compromised the drum itself. Veolia will review this incident with all employees in regards to checking the drum to make sure that it is not compromised and if there is any surface corrosion to further evaluate and potentially place in salvage drum prior to transportation when there is doubt.

column42: FORMIC ACID WITH NOT LESS THAN 5% BUT LESS THAN 10% ACID BY MASS
column168: On 9/28/2023 a Veolia employee unloading drums from a truck into another trailer at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY 10 day intransit facility when the employee noticed that a 14 gallon fiber drum was stained and damp. The 14 gallon drum contained a 2.5 gallon glass bottle of Formic Acid With Not Less Than 5% But Less Than 10% Acid By Mass corrosive liquids. The outer container was opened and the inner container was inspected and was found to be broken and released its contents. No liquid was released from the outer packaging drum.   The 14 gallon drum containing the broken glass bottle was overpacked into an 30 gallon 1H2 drum and transportation to the ultimate disposal facility was continued. The drum did not leak any amount of the corrosive liquid solution out of the outer container.
column169: On 9/28/2023 the Veolia safety manager was notified of the spill. The results of the investigation is the employee who packaged the container did not know that the maximum allowable size of a glass container is limited to one gallon. We did follow up with that employee and reviewed 49 CFR 173.12(b)(2)(i). We will review this requirement with all other employees to make sure they are trained on the limit for glass containers being restricted to one gallon when packaged for transportation in accordance with 49 CFR 173.12.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal NWR experienced a UN1791 "Dynachlor" release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 200-gallons of product released to a 20' x 30' area of the concrete dock floor and a 100' x 50' area of the asphalt lot below. Absorbents and neutralizer were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The remaining product was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbents and cleanup debris into (6) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed soda ash and absorbents to the UN3265-impacted dock and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents and debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon super sack. LSH personnel patched and placed the damaged 55-gallon drum of product into one (1) 95-gallon drum.

column168: SequenceEvent: PKG DAMAGED DURING SORTATION. PLACED INSIDE A LINED HAZMAT TOTE INSIDE THE HAZMAT CAGE FOR EVALUATION. DescribePack: ONE OF THE CONTENTS WAS BROKEN DUE TO DROPPING THE PKG. WHIC CAUSED INTERNAL LEAKAGE. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: TURNED UPRIGHT

Prior driver delivered before this driver into tanks 4 and 5 and the vents are all manifold together.  Driver checked QT app before loading at the rack and dialed back the loaded gallons from 8000 to 7500.  Driver pulled up to store and completed paper work and veeder root reading.  Driver put cones out.  Driver stick the tanks to confirm the stick readings were 2 inches under the veeder root reading.  Driver loaded 3 compartments into tank 6 with no issues.  Driver loaded last compartment into tank 7.  Compartment started to slow down on unloading, driver shut external valve and kept internal open.  Driver cleared product hose and moved it back to tank 6.  Product started to over flow out of tank 7.

On 09/13/2023, at 0239 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parkersburg Yard discovered OLNX 32004, a residue tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and West Virginia DEP were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2023-0913-00015). Quick Response, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the fill hole cover closed however gasketing material was displaced and preventing a proper seal resulting in a vapor release of lading. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Rob Cline of Tetra Technologies, phone 304-482-7655. Contractor personnel properly installed the gasket and fill port cover without incident thus securing the release. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 232 NARRI: 90

column168: On September 24, 2023 at 20:37 Transportation personnel in the Conrail Livernois Terminal reported that ,GATX 2013  a loaded tank car of FLUOROSILICIC ACID leaking from top of the tank car upon movement. Additionally,  during routine switching operations a Conrail Conductor was splashed with acid from the improperly secured tank car. The Conductor was immediately brought in to remove affected clothing and shower of any impacted skin. No reportable injury was encountered as the Conductors and Terminal Supervisions actions removed all material before any health effects took place. The car was isolated and the shipper/consignee PVS was notified directly via phone. Enviroserve, an approved Conrail Contractor was notified to respond, inspect and secure the tank car. Enviroserve personnel, investigated the leak and found the source of the leak to be from the rupture disk assembly. Upon further inspection it was found that the inspection cap was hanging off the housing and no rupture disk was in place beneath the assembly. Additionally, there was no required surge protection on the rupture disk assembly. Enviroserve placed the appropriate rupture disk and resecured the assembly. The tank car was then held until the proper surge protection device could be placed in the assembly. Conrail and Enviroserve worked with the car owner and Steve Kuz, Alltrantec 519-718-8377 to secure the proper service equipment.  On October 4, 2023 the new surge protection device was installed on the tank car and it was released back into transportation.    Cause Code: 437 5 x ( 5 + 5 + 0 ) x ( 2+ 2 ) =  200
